text: Huts 9 and 10 In 1941, the Wehrmacht was planning to build 24 huts to house 20,000 POWs, but only five of them were hastily erected. Hut 9 was used as a depot, while hut 10 was initially used to house prisoners from the special camp. By the summer of 1944, however, a large number of these prisoners had been deported to Auschwitz-Birkenau. The SS then also housed prisoners from the Hungarians’ camp in this hut. They were kept strictly separate from the few remaining special camp prisoners. In mid-January 1945, when the men’s camp was expanded, hut 10 became part of this camp section and was completely overcrowded with male prisoners. The men, who suffered from serious diseases and malnutrition when they arrived at Bergen-Belsen, were isolated and received no food. Almost none of the prisoners in hut 10 survived.

text: The concentration Camp, Introduction The Bergen-Belsen concentration camp was part of the official concentration camp system from the time it was established in April 1943. Today, many consider it the embodiment of Nazi crimes. However, Bergen-Belsen differed from all other Nazi concentration camps in several key aspects. Bergen-Belsen was initially set up for Jewish hostages whom the SS had said they would release - in exchange for Germans interned abroad, foreign currency or commodities valuable to the war effort. The character of the camp changed in March 1944 when a new section was established for sick male prisoners from other concentration camps who were no longer able to work. A section for female prisoners was set up in August 1944. In December 1944, the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp became the destination for numerous evacuation transports from other concentration camps. The camp’s subsequent overcrowding and disastrous living conditions led to mass deaths which claimed the lives of around 18,000 victims in March 1945 alone. At least 52,000 of the total of around 120,000 prisoners in Bergen-Belsen died of starvation or disease, of the abuse they received from the SS, or of the immediate effects of their imprisonment following their liberation.

text: The POW camp, Introduction From 1940, the huts of the former construction workers’ camp were used to house 600 French and Belgian POWs. Starting in May 1941, it was transformed into an independent camp known as Stalag XI C which was intended to hold 20,000 Soviet POWs. Two other so-called “Russian camps” were set up nearby at Oerbke and at Wietzendorf. Around 41,000 Soviet POWs had died in these camps of starvation, exhaustion and disease by the end of March 1942, and a total of 50,000 Soviet POWs died there by the end of the war. Stalag XI C was disbanded in the summer of 1943, and Bergen-Belsen became a branch camp of Stalag XI B at Fallingbostel. It remained in operation as the central hospital for Soviet POWs in the region until January 1945. Italian military internees were treated there as well from August 1944. After the suppression of the Warsaw Uprising in October 1944, around 1,000 members of the Polish Home Army were also housed in a separate section of the POW camp.

text: Perpetrators The Wehrmacht was responsible for housing, feeding and guarding the POWs. The POWs were guarded by soldiers who could not be deployed to the front because of their age or physical afflications. The camps' headquarters were staffed with reserve officers, many of whom were over 60 years old and had already served in World War I. The guidelines for the conduct towards Soviet POWs issued by the Wehrmacht High Command demanded a ruthless treatment of these prisoners without any respect for martial or international law. Many soldiers acted accordingly, others sometimes used the leeway they had to the to prisoners advantage. The first guards squads to be deployed at Bergen-Belsen exchange camp came from the recently disbanded Niederhagen concentration camp. Niederhagen's commandant, SS-Sturmbannführer Adolf Haas, became the first commandant of Bergen-Belsen concentration camp. In July 1943, the commandant of the Theresienstadt ghetto, SS-Hauptsturmführer Dr Siegfird Seidl, was transferred to Bergn-Belsen. As head of the political department, he was in charge of the exchange prisoners. In December 1944, SS-Hauptsturmführer Josef Kramer replaced Haas as commandant. Prior to this, Kramer had been commandant of the Auschwitz-Birkenau extermination camp. He also brought female SS guards to Bergen-Belsen for the first time. Between April 1943 and April 1945, at least 480 SS guards were posted to Bergen-Belsen, among them around 45 female guards.

text: Death and dying Hunger and disease were the main death causes of the mass deaths that occurred in Bergen-Belsen. text: 27 August 1944 Diary entry Translated from the Dutch On the other hand, if it continues to rain, what will I do with my legs? You not get my drift, do you? That is because you do not know the meaning of space. You have a few cubic metres to yourself. You call it ‘room’. In that room you have placed some objects, called chairs and tables, and when you want to eat, you sit yourself at a table on a chair, and in such a way that every person in the room has a chair, and in front of him on the table enough space for his plate and a piece of bread. There are even chairs to spare in the room. When it rains, though … where and how must I eat then? When the sun shines, we sit outdoors. Outdoors there are tables, benches and stools. True, there is not enough room for everyone at once, but one can wait, or rather, can let another wait. When it rains, though, we are unable to sit outdoors. Indoors it is like a Jewish warehouse; the coffins in which we sleep are piled three high, with only twenty centimetres between them. So where must we eat then? We eat together, my wife and I. We sit on her bunk. Below us is a Greek tailor with his wife and child. Fortunately, there is no one above us yet. In my wife’s hut the beds are still only two-tiered. Hence the Greek tailor together with his wife and child are able to sit below us, because there is adequate space between the first and the second bunks. If the beds are three-tiered, the legs of the beds have been shortened. The distance between the first two tiers is then most fifty centimetres, so that one can sit only on the top bunk. If you are lucky, there may even be a further ten centimetres or so of space between your head and the rafters. But in either case the problem is always one’s legs. In our case, the Greek tailor and his wife are not at all pleased that we clamber on top to eat and sit there. The roads are muddy and dirty, and my shoes are like the road! And it is not pleasant to see the shoes of a fellow citizen dangling above your meagre soup, not once, but day after day, week after week, month after month, as they did last winter. The worthy pastor will say people ought to love one another. But the worthy pastor has void which he calls a room, his room, and he has a chair, his chair, and a table, his table. I should like to know what his love for mankind would be like if every morning, every afternoon and every evening my legs were to dangle above his slice of bread, his soup, his gravy, meat, vegetables, potatoes – an dessert. We long for some space. My Greek tailor does protest occasionally, but I think to myself: my dear man, you are an angel. And I am able to think it all the more, because I cannot understand the curses he undoubtedly casts my way. […]

text: 30 August 1944 Diary entry Translated from the French “BB, 30 August ’44. […] This regular roll-call goes on for at least two to three hours every day. And very often, almost every two days, it is extended on some pretext or because of some ‘accident’ to last five to six hours or even the whole day in any kind of weather. But apart from these regular roll-calls, we also often have to line up because of some absurd order, no matter what the time of day, and listen to some announcement. Then two or three officers arrive, review the roll-call, and woe betide those who dare to move and thus disturb the ‘order’. It’s a harrowing image, especially when you see old men or women, for example from the southern parts of our country, shivering from cold and fear before one of these criminals, a Prussian sapling. They embody a whole human life, lived modestly and honestly, in most cases also many years of hard, diligent labour and the traditional respect for other human beings, and now they’re completely reduced to standing to attention in front of some villain who spits his mad rage in their faces and tramples on their souls and human dignity. […]"

text: February 1945 Diary entry Translated from te French "BB. February 1945. I share my bed with Mrs. G., a fairly corpulent woman in her fifties who has been literally immobilized by disease, hunger, and nicotine. Confined to her bed, heavy and inert like lead, she never gets up. All day long, I don't know what to do with my body; I can't get the slightest space in this damned bed to rest my slowly atrophying limbs a little. Breathing has become nearly impossible for me, too. In the evening, I sink into our shared, damp hole on the lowest level of a bed whose upper two levels are occupied by three adults and two children. Our bed is right next to the wall, or rather, those worm-eaten planks that rain seeps through ceaselessly. The window and the door are also nearby. The dampness has penetrated everywhere, soaking everything, clothing, bodies, blankets... Things aren't damp here, they're drenched. Water and mud everywhere, inside and out. And along with them, the air saturated by the suffocating odor exhaled by those suffering from typhus and the stench of urine. Is this a bed? Call it what you want, but not a bed. A muddy swamp. Climbing out of this hole in the morning, my face is completely swollen, my eyelids are sealed, and it takes an hour or two for me to be able to open my eyes and see clearly around me. Each time I wonder if I've gone blind. This is certainly not a bed, it's a tomb - a tomb built for two."

text: 22 April 1944 Diary entry Translated from the Dutch “Saturday, 22 April 1944. […] The so-called shoe factory is located inside a brick-built stable. Around 120 women work in a single room. We sit on these terribly hard stools at wooden tables amid piles of old shoes. The muggy, dusty air makes breathing difficult, and very soon your back begins to hurt from permanently sitting in a crouched position. Our daily quota is to rip up 40 pairs of old shoes, unstitch them seam for seam with unsuitable tools. The parts are then sorted and thrown into Wehrmacht helmets that have been provided for the purpose. Our diligent labour is supposed to win Germany the victory! One helmet is marked for reusable leather, another for scraps, and yet another for pieces of fabric. The “good” pieces are those that the Germans want to make composition leather from. Our favourite helmet is the one intended for the leather scraps. It always fills up fastest, because cutting up good leather into small scraps is the only opportunity for sabotage open to us. The fabric, which sounds much too good a term for those dusty, dirty rags, is desperately needed in the latrines, but more on that later. In total, there may be around 600 men and women crouching over those shoes. Sure, the work may not really be all that hard, but crouching on a rickety wooden stool for eleven hours, hungry and freezing, that’s enough to do us in. And then there’s that awful dust. Your throat gets dry, your eyes get sore and your back hurts between the shoulder blades. I’m sore from sitting down for so long, my stomach hurts, but what hurts the most is the pain I feel from doing this inhumane, useless and empty work. And then there’s the eternal talk about food. People constantly think up new meals that never get served, or dream up ever more imaginative dishes they never taste. They don’t talk about anything else but food! The only relief from this monotonous daily routine is when you get to secretly smoke a cigarette during latrine break. The latrine is a simple wooden cabin with an iron bar over a cesspit, and this is also where all the political rumours originate that are flying around the camp.”

text: The punishment for stealing bread Excerpt from a personal account “Because I was German, I was unfortunately left in charge of a group of foreign comrades on timber detail. The camp’s timber yard was immediately adjacent to the crematorium and was surrounded by a fence. In this enclosure stood another wooden hut. I later discovered that several loaves of bread had been stacked up there. I used my hatchet to break off two boards and took four wholemeal loaves, which I distributed among my comrades. They were so hungry that they gobbled it down, which wasn’t all that easy because the bread was so dry. [...] Then I had to report with the work detail to the Blockführer. [...] The Blockführer immediately asked me if I had stolen bread. My answering in the negative did not help me, because the guards had searched the prisoners and had discovered that most of them had hidden bits of bread on their person. [...] The punishment [of 25 blows] was administered with the leg of a stool under the supervision of the SS Blockführer and the camp elder. I experienced the first three blows before I blacked out. text: Food rations Diary entry Translated from the Polish “I continue my lectures for a group of six youths. Our topic: ‘state and society’. Our current daily ration: ‘coffee – soup – coffee’. The contents of the soup: cabbage and carrots or turnips, sometimes a bit of potato. There are also 300 grams of bread, 12.5 grams of butter and 25 grams of jam daily. Once a week a piece of bad sausage (‘blood sausage’). Every two weeks a piece of cheese (circa 60 grams). Three times a week instead of ‘coffee’ (dark dishwater) there’s thin soup again (those assigned to work receive additional soup). These rations are not always adhered to; there is often no bread. text: Food rations From a personal account written in June 1945 in St. Maur, France “The food has grown significantly worse since the move. At midday we now receive a soup made of cabbage or spinach, but which has almost no fat. For our bread there is margarine instead of butter, and instead of the good jam there is an acidic compote. We haven't received our evening soup for a whole month. We all feel bad, we are all constantly hungry and irritated. We’ve never quarrelled so much before. Acquaintances fight, impatient mothers hit their children, married couples have on-going wars of words. If we receive a few days’ worth of bread rations, we use a knife to mark how much of the bread we can eat each day. Anyone who can’t control themselves eats their entire ration in the first days and has to go without bread in the last days. Then you just lie in bed. It’s easier to bear the hunger lying down."

text: Moving in February 1945 From a personal account written in June 1945 in St. Maur, France "We’re supposed to move again, and this time we’re happy about the change. The huts are damp. There are many holes in the roof, and when it rains, the rain drips on the heads and bedding of the inhabitants of the top bunks. Anyone who has a canopy hangs it above their bunk. But anyone who doesn’t have one, like most of us, is exposed to the wetness. Blankets and pillows are permanently damp, even the bread, which is kept in a box at the end of the bed. Rheumatism troubles us greatly. But this move is delayed day after day, for weeks. Finally [...] we move into our huts, which are far from ours at the edge of the forest. Our neighbours are the Hungarians who came here five weeks ago from a labour camp. They look terrible. Gaunt, starving, ragged figures. They stand at the wire mesh fence and delouse themselves all day long. Their clothing, their blankets, their bodies are ridden with lice. We’ve never seen anything like it. The hut is narrow. 450 people live, sleep and eat in a long room. We have three-tier bunks. Two people have to sleep on each tier. It gets more and more crowded. Mothers sleep with their children, married couples sleep together. I sleep with Micki, my husband sleeps with a colleague. No one can sleep well. But we’re all getting weaker and hungrier. Many of us have swollen legs, swollen faces. Many are still suffering from as yet unhealed abdominal typhus. I’m already so weak that I can no longer walk. Even speaking is an effort for me. I can only whisper. I can barely look after Micki anymore. I have no strength."

text: Situation in the women's camp Excerpt from a personal account Translated from the French "Transports are still arriving from Auschwitz. Nearly 10,000 women are now crammed together in the tents. Their situation is even worse than ours. It’s November, it often rains and it’s already cold. The ground is pure mud. During work I could not avoid, I pass by their section and see what’s happening there. The toilets are simple holes dug in the ground, over which you have to crouch in front of everyone, but that’s something neither they nor we even notice anymore. Washbasins have been hastily set up in the open air for their hygiene. In the tents, the straw has long disintegrated into dust, and the ground is often sodden. text: Catastrophic living conditions Excerpt from a personal account Translated from the French "What you must remember is that the camp is designed to hold 15,000 prisoners, including the POWs, and suddenly the total number of occupants rises to 45,000! The entire operation and the facilities are overstretched. The rations are getting smaller and smaller. The soup is brought at ridiculous times and has practically no nutritional components. The showers are no longer in operation because that would be too much work, and undergarments – they stopped distributing them long ago – aren’t given to us again until the end. There are almost no more medications in circulation. No more soap. Misery, hunger, filth and lice rule over 45,000 men and women."

Then the SS resorts to a pyre. It’s early March. [...] The pyres are large trenches within the fence around the crematorium hut. They are about 20 by 10 metres long and three metres deep. Wood and branches are laid in the bottom. Then comes a layer of corpses, then another layer of wood, a layer of corpses, a layer of wood, etc., multiple layers on top of one another. text: The corpse detail Excerpt from a personal account Translated from the French “To remedy this situation, the SS men then put together the most gigantic and macabre death detail that I have ever seen. All of the prisoners who can stay on their feet are driven out of the blocks, and in groups of four they tie cords or parts of braces or belts around the limbs of a dead prisoner and drag the body in this way for more than a kilometre to the mass graves. If only there had been an illustrator to record for all time this extraordinary procession, which surpassed the most morbid of fantasies! On the way there they walk one behind the other in the midst of the dust kicked up by the bodies dragged over the ground, these horrifying groups of living ghosts; as they drag this unknown comrade by his four skeletal limbs to his final resting place, which will soon be theirs as well, his head bangs against the stones along the way and scrapes roughly along the earth.”

text: Selection for an exchange Diary entry Translated from the Dutch “Thursday, 26 April. Yesterday a transport made up of six Palestine lists comprising older men and women came to Hut 10 (where we were in quarantine). It’s said that they are going to be exchanged to Palestine, something which provokes much discussion. The chance of exchange has passed for me, because it turns out that they will not take anyone fit for military service; the most I can hope for is internment. It was a barbaric process. The day before, Palestine people had to step forward during the work roll-call, a few bigwigs came along, someone read out the names of around 250 people who lined up. After that had gone on for about two hours, in the pouring rain, we who had not been called were allowed to go back home, and we earned ourselves an afternoon off, while those who had been called were given instructions. The next day, again at the work roll-call, which the non-workers were now also ordered to attend, another 250 people were called, but then some others as well who were given fifteen minutes time, all of them elderly or women and children. After that we marched to work without a farewell, not even from Uncle Abel; but there are also men whose wives are going away. The ‘ten’ are now strictly isolated from the rest of the camp, barbed wire and guards. The work will not do me in, but in the long run the hunger and lack of sun probably will."

text: Bread as camp currency Diary entry Translated from the Dutch "You pay for everything with bread here. An eighth of a large loaf is one day’s ration. For that you can get: a week’s ration of butter (!), four spoons of sugar, 8 cigarettes (wait, a transport is suddenly coming in, totally unexpected, forty women!), ... two rations of good or three rations of bad food. It costs one ration to repair shoes, two for the soles. Some manage to save five rations. Others are able to steal just as much. One to three rations are always being withheld from people who work. Damn! Unlike in Amsterdam, coffee and tea are worth almost nothing on account of the lack of hot water, milk and sugar."

text: Situation in the Star Camp, March 1945 "A year ago Mams and I looked at each other: We’re trapped. The repugnant smell of turnips filled the air. (I would give a lot for a bowl of soup from back then, which still contained fat and a bit of meat and potatoes. We haven’t seen any fruit, any eggs or any butter for a year. Epidemic typhus is running rampant, everyone has lice, and we’re still alive. In many larger cities in Europe the yoke has already been thrown off and the new age has begun. They’ve crossed the Rhine; the bombing is continuous, just like last year.) [...] I can barely work anymore, my legs are giving in, and I see no chance of escaping the grip of this hospital. The most delicious thing I can imagine is a bowl of barley soup – something I never ate before –, freshly buttered bread with peanut butter, a rusk with chocolate sprinkles. My fantasies lack all refinement. The daily reality: 250g bread, sour, stale, usually dry and nonetheless wonderful. 1 (2/3) litre turnips, boiled in water, sometimes not even with salt. Four times a week, even in the evenings, a soup made of turnips or flour or bread; the maximum number of calories one gets from this is calculated to be a thousand, before the last bread reduction. A topping for the bread is plus or minus nihil." Diary entry Translated from the Dutch

text: Work details within the camp Interview excerpt; length: xx sec. Interview conducted on 11 September 2009 at the Bergen-Belsen Memorial. Overall length: 5:13 hrs. "You know, there were these magazines – what do I mean by magazines, they were these sheds, magazines. That’s where we cut these turnips into pieces, and where these marinades were kept that were made in the kitchen, because there was also a giant hall where food was stored. Later they brought Kramer there to show it to him. And we were often led out of this hut... There were Dutch Jews there, two SS men, one was a man but the other was worse, he was quick-tempered, that was the boss, and the first was supposedly a Czech. A Dutch Jewish woman worked in the office, and other than us there were only Dutch Jewish women there. There was Lotte, Hermann, someone else I can’t remember. And sometimes, when bread was delivered, we had to bring it into the camp, to the Germans’ food storeroom, where Dutch Jews worked. [...] We had to pull these turnips on a kind of cart with wheels, we loaded the turnips from the storage clamps onto these carts, and I was on the drawbar together with Jadwiga Krasinska. Since I was born in the countryside, I figured that I could go on the drawbar – I said: “I was born in the countryside, I’m going on the drawbar.” So I was on the drawbar on the left side, Jadwiga was on the right, her sister Danuta was already in this... We loaded these turnips, the cart was fully loaded and sometimes the wheels sank into the earth. And then this Hermann, he was a Kapo, but he was ‘very good’, he helped us pull out the cart by the spokes so that we could continue on. There were Ukrainian women, too, they were stronger than us, and the first time they helped us get out again, but the second time they said ‘niet’. text: Daily Life [missing translation] Der Alltag im Konzentrationslager Bergen-Belsen war zwischen den Bereichen des Austauschlagers und dem Männer- und Frauenlager sehr unterschiedlich. Im Verlauf der Lagerzeit verschlechterten sich die Bedingungen darüber hinaus für alle Häftlinge gleichermaßen. Für die Häftlinge im Austauschlager richtete die SS zunächst eine Selbstverwaltung ein, die unter anderem für die Ordnung im Lager, die Einteilung zu den Arbeitskommandos, die Zuteilung auf die Baracken und den Kontakt zur SS verantwortlich war. Während im Sternlager eine Arbeitspflicht für alle erwachsenen Häftlinge galt, waren die Häftlinge im Neutralen-, Sonder- und Ungarnlager davon ausgenommen. Für Kinder wurde zeitweilig in kleinen Gruppen heimlicher Unterricht organisiert und mit vereinzelten kulturellen Darbietungen versuchten die Häftlinge des Austauschlagers, sich abzulenken und als Menschen selbst zu behaupten. Im Frauen- und Männerlager bestand von Beginn an das System der Funktionshäftlinge. Die SS übertrug einzelnen Häftlingen Funktionen und Aufgaben. Sie wurden zu sogenannten Kapos, Lagerältesten, Block- und Stubenältesten bestimmt; Häftlinge wurden als Pfleger und Ärzte eingesetzt. Sie hatten in ihren jeweiligen Positionen Macht über andere Häftlinge und Möglichkeiten, Mithäftlingen zu helfen. Die räumliche Enge durch die große Überfüllung der Baracken und die völlig unzureichende Ernährung prägte den Alltag aller Häftlinge. Die täglichen Appelle, die die SS oft stundenlang abhalten ließ, bedeuteten für die entkräfteten Häftlinge eine ständige und häufig tödliche Qual. Darüber hinaus lebten sie in dem dauernden Bewusstsein der willkürlichen Schikanen durch SS oder Funktionshäftlinge.

Mostly soups were made out of predominantly vegetables and insufficient amounts of salt and fat. Held in large kettles, the soups were carried by prisoners to the camp sections and distributed there. text: Liberation and its aftermath With the front approaching, the Wehrmacht and the SS surrendered Bergen-Belsen concentration camp peacefully to the British army in the context of a local truce and before most of the prisoners had been evacuated. The British troops were in no way prepared for the inferno they were confronted with when they arrived at Bergen-Belsen on the afternoon of 15 April 1945. They immediately implemented relief measures which were continued and intensified over the following days and weeks. Despite all efforts to save the prisoners, the dying in Bergen-Belsen continued. By mid-May, another 12,500 liberated prisoners had died of the effects of their incarceration. Already in 1945 memorials stones and monuments were put up by survivors on the site of the former POW and concentration camp. In 1952 the Memorial was inaugurated after an obelisk and a wall of inscriptions were built. Until today, changes of the Memorial also reflect a changing political and societal situation.

text: Roll call Each of the strictly separated camp sections at the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp had its own roll-call square. The SS held roll calls every day and in any kind of weather to count the thousands of prisoners. During these roll calls, prisoners had to stand to attention, usually in rows of five. Additional roll calls were also held, sometimes several times a day. The many roll calls represented a permanent physical and psychological strain for the prisoners. Particularly sick or old prisoners and children found it very hard to stand to attention for prolonged periods. text: Arrival at the Women's camp "We had to line up again in rows of five. Stiff from sitting, dirty and crumpled, we stood at the train station of Bergen-Belsen. [...] After a two-hour march by foot, during which we even occassionally sang a Dutch song, we reached the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp. The camp was in the middle of the woods. But was it really a camp? We could only see large tents. From these shelters a screaming and noise arose, you did not know what hit you. Were there girls living in there? Was it worse here than in Auschwitz? Our eyes searched for the chimneys, the ovens, but no, smoke was nowhere to be seen, nor were there gas chambers. Would we reach freedom at last? As we were walking through the gate, we were counted by four to five SS men. We passed by one after another and as the last one had gone through, the gate closed behind us, and we were locked up again, our freedom had been taken. As we were walking one after another each of us became two amazing woolen army blankets and a small pot with a spoon. Such luxury! Woolen blankets, a clean spoon and a clean pot. We were brought to a large field, where small heath bushes were growing here and there. We were standing there for hours, without food, without drinks, tired, cold and sad. The screams in the tents in front of us continued, and after a while the volume seemed twice as high. We did not understand. In the distance, pots with food were carried around. Was there a great hunger here as well? For the first time we saw the girls, that lived in Bergen-Belsen. Upon our arrival it had been strictly forbidden to get in touch with us. Everything had been shielded by the SS. Now, during the food distribution, we saw the girls. Oh, how shocked we were. In striped clothes and jackets these poor creatures were walking around, without socks, without stockings, without shoes, no headscarves, nothing. Their faces were emaciated, hollow from hunger. What hell could we expect once again? The Germans had lied to us again. There were no factories here. There were no decent huts. There was no sanitary. No, just misery, dirt and hunger. Our illusions dissolved." Excerpt from a personal account Translated from the Dutch

text: Meeting Anne Frank again "We were in Bergen-Belsen. Everyone would become tin bowl, a spoon and a blanket again. Jannie and I were lucky, at the end of the queue many people did not get anything anymore. We were freezing, we put our blankets around ourselves and were tired as hell. But we were relieved. There were no gas chambers here, nor was there a crematorium... Finally, we got something to eat, a soup with a few pieces of turnip. Turnip was something special. Then we could walk around freely. Someone told us, that we could wash ourselves somewhere on a small hill. We walked and there was a long water pipe with many taps. To wash ourselves with fresh, cold water, had not been possibly since Auschwitz. We covered ourselves in our blankets again, and then two skinny, close shorn figures walked towards us, they looked like small freezing birds. We hugged each other and cried. They were Margot and Anne Frank. We asked them about their mother. Anne just said: "selected". The four of us went back to the roll-call square, we passed by barracks. Then we reached multiple large tents, it looked like a circus had settled here. We were put into these tents. We were laying on straw and huddled together under our blankets. During the first days it was quiet, we slept a lot. It started to rain. Even our blankets could not keep us warm. There were lice here again too. Then we were called to work. In a hut, we had to tear the soles from old shoes, a laborious task. But we got some soup and bread. Soon our hands started to bleed and discharge pus. Anne and I had to quit the work first, it was simply not possible anymore. Jannie and Margot persisted a little longer." excerpt from a personal account

With the help of all our languages mixed together, they ask us for news and food!... The barrack-huts contain a large stove in the middle, long tables and benches, and wooden bunks, three beds high. It’s the first time I've seen three-story bunks; up until now, I'd only seen two. We plump up the straw in the mattresses, so there is room at the end of the bed to squeeze in our suitcases. We sleep with our feet on them. Our first soup at Bergen-Belsen. The other prisoners astonish us by gulping it down, along with ours, which we gladly give them. How can they eat it? The herbs it’s made of are in there with their roots, unwashed, and the dirt crunches between your teeth. text: Roll Call in the Men's Camp "Certain rules apply to us in this roll-call square: We are not allowed to approach the barbed-wire fence and must stay more than two metres away from the huts. These regulations are enforced by a Pole who later became ‘Kapo No. 1’. On account of his two-metre-long cudgel alone, we are at his mercy. When senseless rage grips him, he moves forward like a madman, his jaw clenched in spasms, slavering. He shoos our pathetic herd from one end of the square to the other. Woe be to the one at the back! He once knocked me to the ground with such a blow to my arm that I thought my arm was broken. In the midst of the tumult, there were furious shouts: “We all have to set upon him together and strangle him!” a brave man roars. But everyone quickly runs off, including the brave man. Ultimately, that's less dangerous. Our physical weakness reduces us to a state of total passivity. Up in the watchtower, the guard marvels at the work of the animal tamer." text: Different sections: the Exchange Camp Only a few Jews were explicitly excluded from the racist persecution by Nazi Germany. These were people whom the SS and the German Foreign Office thought might be useful to them in some way. The German Foreign Office and the SS were planning to exchange the Jews imprisoned in Bergen-Belsen for Germans interned by enemy nations or for urgently needed goods and foreign currency or because they were nationals of neutral or friendly states. Starting in July 1943, the SS brought the first exchange prisoners from Greece, from the Westerbork transit camp in the Netherlands and from the ghettos in Poland to Bergen-Belsen. The exchange camp was divided into different sections for the various groups of prisoners that were separated by barbed wire fences. Prisoners could wear their civilian clothes in all camp sections; men and women were housed separately, and children up to the age of 14 stayed with their mothers.

text: Different sections: the Men's and Women's Camps In Bergen-Belsen, too, the SS set up a separate camp section in which sick male prisoners from other concentration camps were housed from March 1944. From mid-August 1944, the SS brought female concentration camp prisoners to Bergen-Belsen. They were initially housed in tents in a provisional camp section and later in huts. Several thousand of these female prisoners were taken from there to the satellite camps at armaments factories to perform slave labour. Many stayed behind, and some of them were also forced to perform slave labour at Bergen-Belsen. Little historical evidence survives to document the suffering and death of these men and women.

text: Labour in the camp While adult prisoners in the star camp were obliged to go to work, prisoners in the other parts of the exchange camp were excluded from this. The “shoe detail” was the largest work detail at the star camp. Its members had to take apart old shoes and cut out reusable pieces of scrap leather. Other work details were regularly working in the kitchens, were doing forestry or worked in construction inside the camp. The prisoners in the men's and the women's camps could sign up for a work detail and got a little extra food as their wage. This chance for better care however meant hard physical labour and the risk of chicanery.

text: Children At least 2,750 children and teenagers were imprisoned in the Bergen-Belsen exchange camp. Most of them arrived there with their parents. Up until the age of 14, children were housed with their mothers. The older ones were put into the men’s or women’s huts respectively. Teenagers in the Star Camp who were over the age of 14 were forced to work on work details. From the moment they arrived at the camp, the children were subjected to the same inhumane camp rules as the adults. They had to stand at roll-call for hours, their lives were confined by barbed wire, and they suffered from hunger and fear. The children were left to their own devices during the day when the adults were forced to work. As hunger, disease and death came to dominate everyday life at the camp during the last months before liberation, the children were increasingly left to their fate. text: Transport of the children "We were herded into the building, which turned out to be the SS garage. When we entered, we saw the luggage our mothers had taken with them and understodd that they must have been ordered to leave it behind in the garage. [...] I was sitting on one of our suitcases when two shadowy figures appeared in the doorway. A torch was lit and shone into the garage. One of the two walked in and switched on the lights. What a sorry sight we must have been. About forty children were huddled together in the corner with tired, tear-stained faces. As I was the nearest one, the guards asked me where we came from. I told him that we had come from Sternlager at about four o'clock that afternoon. [...] I walked back to where the small children were sitting huddled together on the floor. Their eyes swollen from crying, they were totally exhausted by their ordeal. The worst of the wailing had quietened down. They were spent. Some of the little ones were even asleep on the cold concrete floor. [...] Everybody was so very tired from the long, long hours on our feet, the traumatic upheaval we had experienced, as well as having had nothing to eat all day. It became quiet now. Most of the little one were sleeping. By now the older ones were talking to each other in low tones, all afraid to go to sleep. I was tired but not sleepy. About an hour after the guard had left us, he returned with two male prisoners who each carried a large carton. At the same time, a car arrived. Two men entered the garage with their arms full of blankets. I recognized the men from our camp. When Mr Weiss had found out that we were being held in the SS garage, they arranged for the blankets to be delivered to us. How they had been able to arrange this was a mystery to me, but we were very glad as now the older children could have some covers as well.[...] It was now half-past eleven. The chilly outside air penetrated the garage. Trucks could be heard coming down the road. They stopped in front of the garage, Then two SS officers and a female guard entered. Most of the children who had been asleep woke up; a few kept sleeping from sheer exhaustion. We were told to move unto the trucks." Excerpt from a personal account

text: Main camp street The camp’s main street, a six-metre-wide sand track, was built in 1941 during the expansion of the POW camp. It ran for more than a kilometre from the main entrance near the road to the last huts on the opposite side of the camp. It lay at the centre of the 70-metre-wide area between the huts for POWs and those for concentration camp prisoners. This part of the camp also contained facilities such as kitchens, fire water reservoirs and food depots. The main street was under permanent watch by the guards. Camp inmates were only allowed to use it on work assignments during the day and had to be accompanied by guards.

text: The Concentration Camp, Introduction The Bergen-Belsen concentration camp was part of the official concentration camp system from the time it was established in April 1943. Today, many consider it the embodiment of Nazi crimes. However, Bergen-Belsen differed from all other Nazi concentration camps in several key aspects. Bergen-Belsen was initially set up for Jewish hostages whom the SS had said they would release - in exchange for Germans interned abroad, foreign currency or commodities valuable to the war effort. The character of the camp changed in March 1944 when a new section was established for sick male prisoners from other concentration camps who were no longer able to work. A section for female prisoners was set up in August 1944. In December 1944, the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp became the destination for numerous evacuation transports from other concentration camps. The camp’s subsequent overcrowding and disastrous living conditions led to mass deaths which claimed the lives of around 18,000 victims in March 1945 alone. At least 52,000 of the total of around 120,000 prisoners in Bergen-Belsen died of starvation or disease, of the abuse they received from the SS, or of the immediate effects of their imprisonment following their liberation.
